        "materials_required": [
            "Plywood/MDF slab for the platform",
            "scrap 2x4 for platform risers",
            "2x2 stud for X and Y axis bars",
            "3 sets of bolts, nuts, washers",
            "Hacksaw"
        ],
        "description": "This project describes how to build a custom rig to take consistent overhead and macro shots using a platform with adjustable X and Y axis bars for camera positioning.",
        "steps": [
            "Cut the plywood/MDF slab to your desired platform size (e.g., 24\" x 24\"). Cut four risers from the 2x4 scrap, each 4 inches tall. Cut two 2x2 studs to 24\" for the X and Y axis bars.",
            "Drill a 1/2\" hole through the riser that will be in the back right corner to attach one of the cross bars. Glue the risers to the MDF platform and clamp them down until the glue dries. Drill a corresponding 1/2\" hole through one of the cross bars to connect it to the riser. Drill multiple 5/16\" holes near the first hole to accept the other cross bar.",
            "Push a bolt through the platform and riser with a washer. Attach the cross bar, another washer, and a wing nut to allow for quick tightening and loosening.",
            "For the second cross bar, drill a 1\" deep hole in the center of one end using a 9/32\" drill bit. Thread a 5/16\" bolt into the hole using a ratchet and wrench until it is tight. Use a hacksaw to cut off the bolt head while holding the cross bar in a vise. Thread a wing nut over the cut bolt head.",
            "Attach the second cross bar to the first using a bolt, washer, and wing nut to create the final camera axis.",
            "Find a bolt that fits the underside of your camera (typically 1/4\"). Use two wing nuts and a washer to secure the camera to the platform."
        ]
    }
